    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-06_letter01_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <note>211</note>
                <p>
                        Pray my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> send me a <hi rend="underline">finished</hi> miniat<damage><unclear>ure<gap></gap></unclear></damage><lb/>
                        head of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LongX1">Lord Longford</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fannys</persName> tho excellent is not mi<damage><gap></gap></damage><lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyX1">Sneyd</persName> says finished enough for the engraver -<lb/>
                        <del>The man who engraved her drawings of <unclear>Needwood</unclear></del><lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HeapT1">Heaphy</persName> told her that in portraits the drawing must be<lb/>
                        <hi rend="underline">highly</hi> finished -</p><lb/>
                    <p>
                        Her original drawings were returned without the<lb/>
                        slightest damage or speck of dust from the engravers<lb/>
                        - I therefore think we may hazard <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyC1" cert="high">Charlottes</persName><lb/>
                        originals - I beg you to send me the original<lb/>
                        of the Knave &amp; slave - of Flannigan &amp; his companion<lb/>
                        &amp; of the French traiteur &amp; French heads -<lb/>
                        You will see by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HeapT1">Heaphy's</persName> letter that the<lb/>
                        originals are necessary.<lb/></p>
                    <p> 
                        <damage><gap></gap></damage> we decided to have engraved at my <damage><gap></gap></damage><lb/>
                        <damage><unclear>ex<gap></gap></unclear></damage>pense under <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HeapT1">Heaphy's</persName> correction of<lb/>
                        The Irish dance.<lb/>
                        Knave &amp; slave<lb/>
                        Traiteur &amp; French heads -</p><lb/>
                    <p>
                        If the engravings do not do justice to the<lb/>
                        originals I will not let them be published<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        If they do I will present them to<lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntW1" cert="medium">Hunter</persName> - In my opinion the handsomest<lb/>
                        present I can make him - <del>and in my<lb/>
                        opinion the</del> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyC1" cert="medium">Miss Sneyd</persName> &amp; her father &amp; mother<lb/>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. John Sneyd</persName> - the Staffords &amp; al who<lb/>
                        have <del>heard of or</del> seen the sketches or heard<lb/>
                        of the manner in which they wil be mentioned<lb/>
                        in my fathers life decidedly approve<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        I beg you however to say nothing about<lb/>
                        this to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis B</persName> - or any one in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> who<lb/>
                        writes to him<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_696_1819-06_letter01_page02.jpg"/>
                        <damage><gap></gap></damage>The engraving outlines is not expensive -<lb/>
                        <damage><gap></gap></damage>shall know in a few days <add>from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HeapT1">Heaphy</persName></add> the expense of having<lb/>
                        <damage><gap></gap></damage>se outlines &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DayT1" cert="high">Days</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DarwE1" cert="high">Darwins</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LongX1">Longfords</persName><lb/>
                        heads engraved - I suppose 100 guineas<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        I have not said a word<lb/>
                        of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny's</persName> health<lb/>
                        So you may believe<lb/>
                        she will not die this time -<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> will have the heads engraved<lb/>
                        - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HeapT1">Heaphy</persName> shall manage the drawings<lb/>
                        He i<unclear>s</unclear> exquisitely careful about his own<lb/>
                        Return h<unclear>is</unclear> letter by first packet<lb/>
                        D<unclear>i</unclear>rect to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WardX1">Ward</persName> - under cover to RH<lb/>
                        Cr<unclear>e</unclear> whenever you are in distress<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        I hope yo<damage><gap></gap></damage> like this<lb/>
                        <unclear>Hands<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></unclear> <damage><gap></gap></damage>- send your<lb/>
                        cloth you <damage><gap></gap></damage>y <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL2">Lovell</persName> if I<lb/>
                        can catch him flying<lb/></p>
                
                    <closer>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine/><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.Edgeworth</persName></address>
                    </closer>   
            </div>
